  "footnotes": [
    "Botai culture (c.3500 BCE): the earliest archaeological evidence of horse domestication comes from Botai sites in north-central Kazakhstan; bit-wear patterns on horse teeth and corrals indicate domesticated horses; this innovation underpinned all subsequent steppe nomadic cultures",
    "Sintashta culture (c.2100–1800 BCE): the probable origin of the chariot (spoked-wheel, horse-drawn war chariot) and possibly of the Proto-Indo-Iranian language branch; Sintashta-derived peoples are the likely ancestors of both the Vedic Indians and Avestan Iranians",
    "Saka peoples: the Iranian-speaking nomadic confederations of the Kazakh steppe; Achaemenid texts call them 'Saka', Greek sources call them 'Scythians'; their burial kurgans (mounds) stretch across the entire Eurasian steppe",
    "Kazakh Khanate zhuz system: the three 'hordes' (Great Uly Zhuz — Semirechye, Middle Orta Zhuz — Saryarka, Small Kishi Zhuz — western steppe) were confederal units with distinct territories; the Small Zhuz sought Russian protection first in 1731 due to Dzungar pressure",
    "Dzungar Khanate (1634–1755) and Actaban Shubyryndy: the last great nomadic empire, Oirat-Mongolian; its devastating campaigns against the Kazakhs (the 'Great Retreat', c.1723–1727) caused mass displacement and are etched in Kazakh collective memory; the Qing destroyed the Dzungars in a genocidal campaign (1755–1758)"
  ]
